text: The man-apes of the field had none of these attributes, a they were on the long, pathetic road to racial extinction About twenty of them occupied a group of caves overlookin a small, parched valley, divided by a sluggish, brown str The tribe had always been hungry, and now it was starving As the first dim glow of dawn creeps into the cave, Moonw discovers that his father has died during the night. He d the Old One was his father, for such a relationship was b his understanding. but as he stands looking down at the e iated body he feels something, something akin to sadness. he carries his dead father out of the cave, and leaves hi hyenas. Among his kind, Moonwatcher is almost a giant. He is near five feet high, and though badly undernourished, weighs o a hundred pounds. His hairy, muscular body is quite man-l and his head is already nearer man than ape. The forehead low, and there are great ridges over the eye-sockets, yet unmistakably holds in his genes the promise of humanity. he looks out now upon the hostile world, there is already
something in his gaze beyond the grasp of any ape. In tho dark, deep-set eyes is a dawning awareness-the first inti tions of an intelligence which would not fulfill itself f two million years.

As the dawn sky brightens, Moonwatcher and his tribe reac the shallow stream. The Others are already there. They were there on the othe side every day - that did not make it any less annoying. There are eighteen of them, and it is impossible to disti them from the members of Moonwatcher's own tribe. As they see him coming, the Others begin to angrily dance an shriek on their side of the stream, and his own people re In kind. The confrontation lasts a few minutes - then the display out as quickly as it has begun, and everyone drinks his f the muddy water. Honor has been satisfied - each group ha staked its claim to its own territory.

Moonwatcher and his companions search for berries, fruit and leaves, and fight off pangs of hunger, while all arou them, competing with them for the samr fodder, is a poten source of more food than they could ever hope to eat. Yet all the thousands of tons of meat roaming over the parche savanna and through the brush is not only beyond their re the idea of eating it is beyond their imagination. They a slowly starving to death in the midst of plenty.

The tribe slowly wanders across the bare, flat country- side foraging for roots and occasional berries. Eight of them are irregularly strung out on the open plai about fifty feet apart. The ground is flat for miles around. Suddenly, Moonwatcher becomes aware of a lion, stalking them about 300 yards away. Defenceless and with nowhere to hide, they scatter in all directions, but the lion brings one to the ground.

It had not been a good day, though as Moonwatcher had no real remembrance of the past he could not compare one day with another. But on the way back to the caves he finds a hive of bees in the stump of a dead tree, and so enjoys t finest delicacy his people could ever know. Of course, he also collects a good many stings, but he scacely notices them. He is now as near to contentment as he is ever likely to be; for thought he is still hungry, he is not a weak with hunger. That was the most that any hominid coul hope for.

Over the valley, a full moon rises, and a cold wind blows from the distant mountains. It would be very cold tonight but cold, like hunger, was not a matter for any real conc it was merely part of the background of life. This Little Sun, that only shone at night and gave no war was dangerous; there would be enemies abroad. Moonwatcher crawls out of the cave, clambers on to a large boulder be the entrance, and squats there where he can survey the va If any hunting beast approached, he would have time to ge to the relative safety of the cave. Of all the creatures who had ever lived on Earth, Moonwat race was the first to raise their eyes with interest to t and though he could not remember it, when he was young, Moonwatcher would reach out and try to touch its ghostly Now he new he would have to find a tree that was high enough. He stirs when shrieks and screams echo up the slope from one of the lower caves, and he does not need to hear the

occasional growl of the lion to know what is happening. D there in the darkness, old One-Eye and his family are dyi and the thought that he might help in some way never cros Moonwatcher's mind. The harsh logic of survival rules out such fancies. Every cave is silent, lest it attract disas And in the caves, in tortured spells of fitful dozing and fearful waiting, were gathered the nightmares of generati yet to come.

The Others are growing desperate; the forage on their sid the valley is almost exhausted. Perhaps they realise that Moonwatcher's tribe has lost three of its numbers during night, for they choose this mourning to break the truce. they meet at the river in the still, misty dawn, there is deeper and more menacing note in their challenge. The noi but usually harmless confrontation lasts only a few secon before the invasion begins. In an uncertainly-moving horde, the Others cross the rive shieking threats and hunched for the attack. They are led by a big-toothed hominid of Moonwatcher's own size and ag Startled and frightened, the tribe retreats before the fi advance, throwing nothing more substantial than imprecati at the invaders. Moonwatcher moves with them, his mind a mist of rage and confusion. To be driven from their own territory is a great badness, but to lose the river is de He does not know what to do; it is a situation beyond his experience. Then he becomes dimly aware that the Others are slowing

down, and advancing with obvious reluctance. The further move from their own side, the more uncertain and unhappy they become. Only Big-Tooth still retains any of his orig drive, and he is rapidly being seperated from his followe As he sees this, Moonwatcher's own morale immediately revives. He slows down his retreat, and begins to make reassuring noises to his companions. Novel sensations fil his dim mind - the first faint precursors of bravery and leadership. Before he realizes it, he is face to face with Big-Tooth, the two tribes come to a halt many paces away. The disorganized and unscientific conflict could have end quickly if either had used his fist as a club, but this innovation still lay hundreds of thousands of years in th future. Instead, the slowly weakening fighters claw and scratch and try to bite each other. Rolling over and over, they come to a patch of stony grou and when they reach it Moonwatcher is on top. By chance,

he chooses this moment to grab the hair on Big-Tooth's sc and bang his head on the ground. The resulting CRACK is so satisfactory, and produces such an immediate weakening In Big - Tooth's resistance, that he quickly repeats it. Even when Big-Tooth ceases to move for some time, Moon- watcher keeps up the exhilirating game. With shrieks of panic, the Others retreat back, across th stream. The defenders cautiously pursue them as far as The water's edge.

Dozing fitfully and weakened by his stuggle, Moonwatcher startled by a sound. He sits up in the fetid darkness of the cave, straining h senses out into the night, and fear creeps slowly into hi Never in his life - already twice as long as most members his species could expect - has he heard a sound like this great cats approached in silence, and the only thing that betrayed them was a rare slide of earth, or the occasiona cracking of a twig. Yet this is a continuing crunching no that grows steadily louder. It seemed that some enormous beast was moving through the night, making no attempt at concealment, and ignoring all obstacles. And then there came a sound which Moonwatcher could not possibly have identified, for it had never been heard bef in the history of this planet.

Moonwatcher comes face to face with the New Rock when he leads the tribe down to the river in the first light of m He had almost forgotten the terror of the night, because had happened after that initial noise, so he does not eve associate this strange thing with danger or with fear. Th is nothing in the least alarming about it. It is a cube about fifteen feet on a side, and it is made some completely transparent material; indeed, it is not e to see except when the light of the sun glints on its edg There are no natural objects to which Moonwatcher can compare this apparition. Though he is wisely cautious of most new things, he does not hesitate to walk up to it As nothing happens, he puts out his hand, and feels a war hard surface. After several minutes of intense thought, he arrives at a brilliant explanation. It is a rock, of course, and it must have grown during the night. There are many plants that do this - white, pulpy things shaped like pebbles, t seem to shoot up in the hours of darkness. It is true tha they are small and round, whereas this is large and squar

but greater and later philosophers than Moonwatcher would prepared to overlook equally striking exceptions to their This really superb piece of abstract thinking leads Moonw to a deduction which he immediately puts to the test. The round pebble-plants are very tasty (though there were a f that made one violently sick); perhaps this square one... A few licks and attempted nibbles quickly disillusion him There is no nourishment here; so like a sensible hominid, continues on his way to the river and forgets all about t

They are still a hundred yards from the New Rock when the sound begins. It is quite soft, and it stops them in their tracks, so t stand paralyzed on the trail with their jaws hanging. A s maddeningly repetitious rhythm pulses out of the crystal and hypnotises all who come within its spell. For the fir time - and the last, for two million year - the sound of drumming is heard in Africa. The throbbing grows louder, more insistent. Presently the hominids begin to move forward like sleep-walkers, toward the source of that magnetic sound. Sometimes they take li dancing steps, as their blood responds to the rhythms tha their descendants will not create for ages yet. Totally entranced, they gather around the Cube, forgettin the hardships of the day, the perils of the approaching d and the hunger in their bellies. Now, spinning wheels of light begin to merge, and the spo fuse into luminous bars that slowly recede into the dista

rotating on their axes as they do; and the hominids watch eyed, mesmerized captives of the Crystal Cube. Then by some magic - though it was no more magical than a that had gone on before - a perfectly normal scene appear is as if a cubical block had been carved out of the day a shifted into the night. Inside that block is a group of f hominids, who might have been members of Moonwatcher's own tribe, eating chunks of meat. The carcass of a wart-h lies near them. This little family of male and female and two children is and replete, with sleek and glossy pelts - and this was a condition of life that Moonwatcher had never imagined. Fr time to time they stir lazily, as they loll at ease near entrance of their cave, apparently at peace with the worl The spectacle of domestic bliss merges into a totally different scene. The family is no longer reposing peacefully outside its c it is foraging, searching for food like any normal homini

A small wart-hog ambles past the group of browsing humano without giving them more than a glance, for they had neve the slightest danger to its species. But that happy state of affairs is about to end. The big suddenly bends down, picks up a heavy stone lying at his and hurls it upon the unfortunate pig. The stone descends its skull, making exactly the same noise that Moonwatcher produced in his now almost forgotten encounter with Big-T And the result, too, is much the same - the warthog gives amazed, indignant squeal, and collapses in a motionless h Then the whole sequence begins again, but this time it un itself with incredible slowness. Every detail of the move can be followed; the stone arches leisurely through the a pig crumples up and sinks to the ground. There the scene freezes for long moments, the slayer standing motionless above the slain, the first of all weapons in his hand. The scene suddenly fades out. The cube is no more than a glimmering outline in the darkness; the hominids stir, as

awakening from a dream, realise where they are, and scutt back to their caves. They have no concious memory of what they had seen; but t night, as he sits brooding at the entrance of his lair, h attuned to the noises of the world around him, Moonwatche feels the first faint twinges of a new and potent emotion to kill. He had taken his first step towards humanity.

EXT cave AND PLAINS - Utopia Babies were born and sometimes lived; feeble, toothless t year-olds died; the lion took its toll in the night; the threatened daily across the river - and the trib prospere In the course of a single year, Moonwatcher and his compa had changed almost beyond recognition. They had become as plump as the family in the Cave, who n longer haunted their dreams. They had learned their lesso well; now they could handle all the stone tools and weapo the Cube had revealed to them. They were no longer half-numbed with starvation, and they had time both for leisure and for the first rudiments of Their new way of life was casually accepted, and they did not associate it in any way with the crystal cube still s outside their cave. But no Utopia is perfect, and this one had two blemishes. first was the marauding lion, whose passion for hominids seemed to have grown even stronger now that they were bet nourished. The second was the tribe across the river; for
somehow the Others had survived, and had stubbornly refus die of starvation.

With the partly devoured carcass of a warthog laid out on ground at the point he hope the boulder would impact, Moo watcher and three of his bravest companions wait for two consecutive nights. On the third the lion comes, betraying his presences by a small pebble slide. When they can here the lion below, softly tearing at the they strain themselves against the massive boulder. The s of the lion stops; he is listening. Again they silently h against the enormous stone, exerting the final limits of strength. The rock begin to tip to a new balance point. The lion twitches alert to this sound, but having no fear creatures, he makes the first of two mistakes which will him his life; he goes back to his meal. The rock moves slowly over the ledge, picking up speed wi amazing suddeness. It strikes a projection in the cliff a fifteen feet above the ground, which deflects its path ou Just at this instant, the lion reacts instinctively and l away from the face of the cliff directly into the path of

onrushing boulder. He has combined the errors of over- confidence and bad luck. The next morning they find the lion in front of the cave. also find one of their tribe who had incautiously peeped see what was happening, and was apparently killed by a sm rock torn loose by the boulder; but this was a small pric pay for such a great victory.
And then one night the crystal cube was gone, and not eve Moonwatcher ever thought of it again. He was still wholly unaware of all that it had done.

From their side of the stream, in the never violated safe their own territory, the Others see Moonwatcher and fourt males of his tribe appear from behind a small hillock ove looking the stream, silhouetted against the dawn sky. The Others begin to scream their daily challenge. But tod something is different, though the Others do not immediat recognize this fact. Instead of joining the verbal onslaught, as they had alwa Moonwatcher and his small band decended from the rise, an begin to move forward to the stream with a quiet purposef never befor seen. As the Others watch the figures silently approaching in t morning mist, they become aware of the terrible strangnes of this encounter, and their rage gradually subsides down an uneasy silence. At the water's edge, Moonwatcher and his band stop. They carry their bone clubs and bone knives.

Led by One-ear, the Others half-heartly resume the battle chant. But they are suddenly confrunted with a vision tha the sound from their throats, and strikes terror into the hearts. Moonwatcher, who had been partly concealed by two males w walked before him, thrusts his arm high into the air. In hand he holds a stoud tree branch. Mounted atop the branc the bloody head of the lion, its mouth jammed open with a displaying its frightful fangs. The Others gape in fearful disbelief at this display of p Moonwatchers stands motionless, thrusting the lion's head Then with majestic deliberation, still carrying his mangl standard above his head, he begins to cross the stream, f by his band. The Others fade back from the stream, seeming to lack eve the ability to flee. Moonwatcher steps ashore and walks to One-Ear, who stands

unsurely in front of his band. Though he is a veteran of numerous combats at the water's One-Ear has never been attacked by an enemy who had not f displayed his fighting rage; and he had never before been with a weapon. One-Ear, merely looks up at the raised clu until the heavey thigh bone of an antelope brings the dar down around him. The Others stare in wonder at Moonwatcher's power. Moonwatcher surveys the scene. Now he was master of the world, and he was not sure what to do next. But he would think of something.
